### PHP try-catch-finally

The `try-catch` block allows you to gracefully handle exceptions.

### Basic try-catch

```php
<?php
try {
    // Code that may throw an exception
    $result = 10 / 0;
    echo "This will not execute";
} catch (DivisionByZeroError $e) {
    echo "Caught: " . $e->getMessage();
}

echo "Script continues...";
?>
```

### Multiple Catch Blocks

```php
<?php
try {
    $file = fopen("test.txt", "r");
    if (!$file) {
        throw new Exception("File not found");
    }
    // Process file...
} catch (InvalidArgumentException $e) {
    echo "Invalid argument: " . $e->getMessage();
} catch (Exception $e) {
    echo "General error: " . $e->getMessage();
}
?>
```

### finally Block

The `finally` block always executes, regardless of whether an exception was thrown.

```php
<?php
function readFile($filename) {
    $file = null;
    try {
        $file = fopen($filename, "r");
        if (!$file) {
            throw new Exception("Cannot open file");
        }
        return fread($file, filesize($filename));
    } catch (Exception $e) {
        echo "Error: " . $e->getMessage();
        return null;
    } finally {
        if ($file) {
            fclose($file); // Always close
        }
    }
}
?>
```

### try-catch Flow

| Block | Executes When |
|-------|---------------|
| `try` | Always (starts execution) |
| `catch` | Exception is thrown in try |
| `finally` | Always (after try or catch) |

> **Key Point:** The `finally` block is ideal for cleanup operations like closing files or database connections that must run regardless of success or failure.
